Ticket ID: AI-OBS-2026-02-24-01
Title: Observational Study on AI Agent Reliability and Hallucination Patterns During Complex File Generation
Classification: AI Usage Analysis / Prompt Engineering Observations
Execution Date: 24 February 2026
Status: Completed
Executive Summary
This activity consisted of documenting observations related to the practical use of large language model assistants during complex tasks, specifically the generation of a legally sensitive financial document (Romanian investment tax tracking file). The objective was to analyze the behavior, limitations, and reliability patterns of AI agents when tasked with generating complex, multi-module outputs requiring legal compliance and technical precision.
The observations gathered during this process led to the redesign of the AI interaction strategy in order to improve reliability and reduce hallucination risk.
Context
The user was attempting to generate a structured investment tracking file designed to support Romanian fiscal reporting requirements. Multiple AI interactions were performed using different agents and prompting strategies.
During this process, the user observed recurring issues when requesting highly complex deliverables in a single prompt or conversation.
Key Observations
Both ChatGPT and Copilot demonstrate strong capabilities when producing long, structured explanations or educational content.
Examples where the agents performed reliably include:
	• vocabulary and grammar explanations for language learning
	• explanations regarding health benefits of ingredients or supplements
	• structured learning plans for acquiring new skills
	• general informational legal explanations
When prompts are clear and structured, both agents are able to produce satisfactory responses.
However, reliability decreases significantly when tasks require the simultaneous execution of multiple complex operations.
Observed Failure Patterns
The agents showed increased hallucination or structural failures when the user attempted to request:
	• research
	• design
	• legal interpretation
	• file generation
	• structured calculations
within the same prompt or conversation.
When these tasks were combined, the agents sometimes:
	• omitted important requirements
	• produced incomplete files
	• forgot previously defined constraints
	• generated partially correct outputs
	• stopped mid-process
A practical example was the attempt to generate a fully compliant Romanian tax tracking Excel file. While multiple versions were generated, each contained structural or fiscal inaccuracies such as:
	• missing FIFO per lot logic
	• incomplete tax logic
	• omitted fiscal considerations
Strategic Conclusion
The original approach of requesting full complex deliverables in a single conversation was abandoned.
The user developed a new methodology based on modular AI interaction.
New AI Usage Strategy
The improved approach includes:
	1. Define the overall objective clearly.
	2. Break the task into small modular requirements.
	3. Implement each requirement in stages.
	4. Validate each stage before continuing.
	5. Save intermediate versions of files.
	6. If necessary, continue development using different AI agents.
This methodology significantly reduces hallucination risk and increases the reliability of AI-assisted work.
